## The question

Global wellbeing data is scattered across separate sources — happiness surveys
live in one place, mental-health prevalence in another, mortality and economic
indicators in two more — and each uses its own country names, codes, and year
ranges. **Could I integrate them into a single interactive tool that lets a
non-technical user explore how these indicators relate across countries and over
time, without writing a line of code?**

## Data

The dashboard integrates **four international sources** into one harmonized panel:

- **World Happiness Report** — national happiness scores
- **WHO** — health system and mortality indicators
- **IHME** — depression and mental-health prevalence
- **World Bank** — population and economic context

Coverage spans **100+ countries, 2010–2020**. The hard part wasn't any single
source — it was reconciling them: aligning country identifiers, harmonizing year
ranges, and handling the inconsistent missingness that appears whenever you join
international datasets that were never designed to fit together.

## What I built

- **An interactive choropleth world map** that recolors by the selected
  indicator — happiness, depression prevalence, life expectancy, mortality, or
  population.
- **A year slider** for exploring temporal trends across the full 2010–2020 range.
- **Dropdown controls** for switching indicators and basemap styles, so a user
  can pivot the whole view without touching code.
- **Country-level drill-down** for reading any single nation's trajectory.

The emphasis throughout was usability for a non-technical audience — a public
health professional or policymaker should be able to answer a question in a few
clicks.

## Tools

Built in **Python with Shiny (PyShiny)** — Shiny's Python framework — handling
data cleaning, integration, and the reactive interactive logic, then **deployed
to shinyapps.io** as a live public application.

